<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-523-796  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 523 796.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  August 14 1989 n232 p36(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Who's afraid of the dark? Some MIS chiefs show no fear as fullyautomated data centers loom.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Leibs, Scott.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Studies show that approximately 75 percent of MIS operations aremoving toward 'lights out,' or fully automated, data centers.andO;Automation software can cut costs and improve service byincreasing machine efficiency and handling tasks traditionallyperformed by computer operators.andP;  Automation of BostonUniversity's information systems has doubled computing capacity,increased direct access storage device usage by 60 percent,programming by 40 percent and service levels uptime from 95percent to 99 percent, while the data center staff has beenreduced by 60 percent and the MIS budget by 25 percent.andP;  Datacenters engaged in automation efforts may be daunted by the numberof automation tools presently on the market, but vendors areincreasingly offering integrated packages.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MISFully AutomatedInformation CentersHuman Factors.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphtable.andO;Caption:   Technology for operations. (graph)Use of operations productivity software. (graph)Selected vendors of automation software. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>